s 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Dorset): apparently from Middle English <i>trivet</i>, <i>trevet</i> ‘trivet, tripod’ (Old English <i>trefet</i>), especially for a three-footed stand for a pot, kettle, or pan placed over a fire during cooking or heating. In Yorkshire, Lincolnshire, and the North Midlands this name has become confused with   Trewhitt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Trewhitt","meanings":["English (Durham and Yorkshire): habitational name from High and Low Trewhitt in Rothbury (Northumberland). The origin of the placename is uncertain. This name has sometimes been confused with   Trevett  ."]},{"name":"Trivett","meanings":["English: variant of   Trevett  ."]},{"name":"Trivitt","meanings":["English: variant of   Trevett  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":27,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Trevett III was born in 1355, in Somerset, England, his father, Thomas Trevett II, was 25 and his mother, Elizabeth of Somerset, was 20. He married Elizabet